<h5 id="public-messaging">Public Messaging<a role="anchor" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1" data-no-popover="true" href="#public-messaging" class="internal"><svg width="18" height="18" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><path d="M10 13a5 5 0 0 0 7.54.54l3-3a5 5 0 0 0-7.07-7.07l-1.72 1.71"></path><path d="M14 11a5 5 0 0 0-7.54-.54l-3 3a5 5 0 0 0 7.07 7.07l1.71-1.71"></path></svg></a></h5>
<p>Also known as forums, public messaging predated social networks and enabled people to communicate with one another by posting messages to a public bulletin board, replying to threads, receiving notifications, and sending private messages. <a href="../../Public-message-boards-were-the-first-example-of-online-public-messaging" class="internal alias" data-slug="Public-message-boards-were-the-first-example-of-online-public-messaging">Public message boards were the first example of online public messaging</a></p>
